Circuit Breaker
================

=> It is one of the most famous design pattern in microservices development.

=> It is used to implement fault tolerent systems.

=> Fault Tolerant systems also called as Resillence systems.


## Requirement : If main logic is failed to execute then we have to execute fallback logic and send success response to client instead of sending error response.

## Usecase : 

main logic : retrieve data from redis cache

fallback logic : retrieve data from database

--------------------------- try-catch approach --------------------------------

class Demo {
	
	public void getData (){
		try{
			m1 ( );
		}catch (Exception e){
			m2( );
		}
	}

	m1 ( ) {
		// get data from redis
	}

	m2 ( ) {
		// get data from db
	}
}

----------------------------------------------------------------

=> In above scenario always m1 () method will be called, when it fails then m2 ( ) method will be called.

=> when m1 ( ) method failing continusouly then why to call it again and again...

Note: We can resolve this problem using Circuit Breaker concept....


=> When m1 ( ) method failing continuously for 5 requests then we shouldn't call m1 ( )for next 30 mins of time... directley call m2 () method... 

Requirement: after 30 mins completed then lets retry calling m1 ( ) method... if it is working then continue with m1 ( ), if it not working then continue with m2 ( ) for another 30 mins... and repeat the retry process for every 30 mins.

Note: We can't achieve above requirement using try-catch blocks thats where Circuit Breaker pattern comes into picture.



=> Circuit Breaker works based on 3 states

		1) CLOSED

		2) OPEN

		3) HALF_OPEN


## CLOSED : System is having normal flow. System working as expected (no need to execute fallback logic).

## OPEN : The circuit interrupted, some fault occured hence normal flow will be stopped and only fallback logic will be executed for given amount time (Ex : 30 mins).	

## HALF_OPEN : System will try for normal flow, if normal flow working as expected then Circuit will go to CLOSED state else it will go to OPEN state.


=> In springboot, we can implement circuit breaker in 2 ways

		1) hystrix (outdated)

		2) Spring Cloud Resillence4J (Trending)




================================
Circuit Breaker Implementation
================================		

#### 1) Create Spring Boot project with below dependencies

		a) web-starter
		b) actuator
		c) aop
		d) resillence4J


<dependency>
	<groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
	<artifactId>spring-boot-starter-aop</artifactId>
</dependency>		


### 2) Create Rest Controller with required methods		


@RestController
public class DataRestController {	
	
	@GetMapping("/data")
	@CircuitBreaker(fallbackMethod = "getDataFromDB", name="ashokit")
	public String getDataFromRedis() {
		
		System.out.println("*** redis() method executed... ***");
		
		return "redis call success";
		
	}
	
	public String getDataFromDB(Throwable t) {
		
		System.out.println("*** db() method executed... ***");
		
		return "db call success";
		
	}
}		

#### 3) Configure CircuitBreaker Properties in application.yml file

---
spring:
  application:
    name: 29-Circuit-Breaker-App
management:
  endpoints:
    web:
      exposure:
        include: '*'
  endpoint:
    health:
      show-details: always
  health:
    circuitbreakers:
      enabled: true
        
resilience4j:
  circuitbreaker:
    configs:
      default:
         registerHealthIndicator: true
         slidingWindowSize: 10
         minimumNumberOfCalls: 5
         failureRateThreshold: 50
         waitDurationInOpenState: 100s
         automaticTransitionFromOpenToHalfOpenEnabled: true
         permittedNumberOfCallsInHalfOpenState: 3
---


#### 4) Test The application and monitor actuator health endpoint to observe Circuit Breaker status. 

	URL To access rest endpoint : http://localhost:8080/data

	URL to monitor CB Status : http://localhost:8080/actuator/health
